    "content": "The BTI 2026 Somalia Country Report paints a grim picture of political and economic stagnation. With a political transformation score of just 1.72 out of 10, Somalia ranks 134th among 137 countries, indicating severe deficits in statehood, political participation, rule of law, and institutional stability. The report notes that a controversial constitutional review during the review period prompted Puntland to withdraw from the Somali Federation, further fragmenting an already fragile state.\n\nOn the economic front, Somalia's transformation score of 1.89 places it 130th globally. Key weaknesses include a socio-economic development level of 1.00, market and competition order at 2.30, and currency and price stability at 2.00. The report highlights a struggling private property regime and welfare system, with economic performance barely above subsistence levels. Sustainability efforts also remain minimal, scoring 1.50.\n\nThe governance index, at 2.48, reflects deep challenges in steering capability (2.70), resource efficiency (1.30), and consensus-building (2.40). International cooperation scores slightly better at 3.70, but overall governance is hampered by a high difficulty rating of 9.40. The report underscores that without significant political consensus and institutional reforms, Somalia's path to recovery remains fraught with obstacles.",
