    "title": "Horn of Africa - Wikipedia",
    "slug": "horn-of-africa-wikipedia",
    "summary": "The Horn of Africa is a peninsula and geopolitical region in East Africa encompassing Djibouti, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Somalia, and Somaliland, with a population of over 140 million.",
    "content": "The Horn of Africa is a prominent peninsula and geopolitical region in East Africa, stretching from the Gulf of Aden to the Indian Ocean. It encompasses the countries of Djibouti, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Somalia, and the de facto independent state of Somaliland. The region covers an area of approximately 1,882,757 square kilometers and has an estimated population of 140,683,144 as of 2020.\n\nGeopolitically, the Horn of Africa is a critical hub for trade and security, given its proximity to major shipping lanes and the Suez Canal. The region is characterized by a diverse mix of ethnicities, languages, and cultures, including Somali, Oromo, Amhara, Tigrayan, and Afar peoples. Major capital cities are Djibouti City (Djibouti), Asmara (Eritrea), Addis Ababa (Ethiopia), Mogadishu (Somalia), and Hargeisa (Somaliland).\n\nIn addition to the sovereign states, several autonomous and self-governing regions exist, including Puntland and Jubaland within Somalia, as well as the Islamic Wilayat of Somalia (also known as Al-Shabaab-controlled territory). The region has faced numerous challenges, including political instability, conflict, drought, and famine, but also possesses significant potential for economic growth through agriculture, livestock, and natural resources.\n\nThe Horn of Africa's strategic importance continues to attract international attention, with foreign powers maintaining military bases and engaging in diplomatic and development efforts. The region's stability is crucial for the broader African continent and global security.",
